In addition to the practices described above, we have designed our processes to include multiple layers of safeguards.  Examples of these include:

A? Computer display and control of process parameters;
A? Interlocks to automatically shut down processes for certain process deviations;
A? HCL monitors in the storage tank area that provide an alarm when a leak is detected;
A? Isolation valves which can be operated remotely from the process control system;
A? Check valves to prevent cross contamination of chemicals;
A? Camera surveillance of process areas in central control rooms;
A? Fire prevention activities like electrical grounding, inerting flammables with nonflammable gases and hot work permitting; and
A? The mechanical integrity of the TFE/HCL and VF2 supply lines is verified by periodic visual inspections and by annual thickness measurements.
A? Flexible unloading hoses that connect the railcar to the chlorine supply line are replaced annually.
A? When hoses are disconnected from the TFE/HCL trailers, the free ends are covered to keep moisture out of the line.

Five Year Accident History

In the past five years, there were no accidental releases of regulated chemicals from the facility resulting in on-site deaths, injuries, or significant property damage, or known off-site deaths, injuries, evacuations, sheltering in place, property damage, or environmental damage.  DPP began operating the Chambers Works facility on Oct 1, 2010 staffing it with Dupont employees. The prior operator of the facility was Dupont Performance Elastomers, LLC a wholly owned subsidiary of DuPont which operated the facility from July 1, 2005 until September 30 2010. DuPont Dow Elastomers LLC a joint venture with Dow Chem
